## The Week at a Glance

- 🔴 **High — Exchange Server 2016/2019 support ends October 2026.** Microsoft has confirmed no further extensions. Organizations still running on-premises Exchange face an unpatched mail server by November, creating a severe security and compliance exposure.
- 🔴 **High — ACR Stealer credential-theft campaign is actively hitting enterprise environments.** Attackers are using convincing fake prompts to steal browser credentials and authentication tokens. This is a live threat requiring immediate employee awareness action.
- 🟡 **Medium — AI agents are proliferating faster than access controls are being applied.** Industry peers report thousands of unmanaged agents operating inside their organizations. Governance frameworks need to be planned and funded now, before the risk compounds.
- 🟢 **Low — Post-quantum encryption protections are now available in Windows 11.** Microsoft has shipped quantum-resistant encryption capabilities via July Windows updates. No immediate action is required, but awareness supports long-term security roadmap planning.

*Sources: [Exchange Team Blog — ESU End Reminder](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/reminder-exchange-2016-and-2019-esu-program-ends-in-october-2026/ba-p/4539033) · [Microsoft Security Blog — ACR Stealer](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/16/acr-stealer-two-observed-intrusion-chains-amid-increased-threat-activity/) · [Microsoft Entra Blog — AI Agent Access Controls](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-entra-blog/ai-agents-are-everywhere-are-your-access-controls-ready/ba-p/4531379)*

---

## Why This Week Matters

Two converging risks stand out this week. First, a confirmed and active credential-theft campaign is successfully bypassing traditional defenses by tricking employees into surrendering their login tokens directly. Second, the Exchange Server deadline is no longer a future planning item; it is a current-quarter operational necessity. The single most important thing leadership must understand is this: both risks are time-bounded, and the cost of delay is measurably higher than the cost of acting now.

*Sources: [Microsoft Security Blog — ACR Stealer](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/16/acr-stealer-two-observed-intrusion-chains-amid-increased-threat-activity/) · [Exchange Team Blog — ESU End Reminder](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/reminder-exchange-2016-and-2019-esu-program-ends-in-october-2026/ba-p/4539033)*

