## What Your Help Desk Should Expect

- **Increased questions about AI answering Teams calls.** Employees unfamiliar with intelligent call delegation may file tickets asking whether their calls are being recorded, who authorized the feature, and how to opt out. Prepare a one-paragraph FAQ for front-line support staff.
- **Copilot appearing in SharePoint without a user requesting it.** Because Copilot in SharePoint is now on by default for licensed users, expect tickets from employees who are surprised to see AI features or confused about what the AI can access.
- **SSO prompt behavior changes on managed Windows 11 devices.** If IT enables the new admin control to suppress SSO prompts, some users may notice the change and inquire whether something is wrong with their account.
- **Exchange patch application questions.** If your organization runs on-premises Exchange, IT teams will be applying the July security updates. Planned maintenance windows should be communicated in advance to reduce disruption tickets.
- **Questions about the Exchange end-of-support deadline.** As awareness grows about the October 2026 deadline, business users may ask IT or leadership what the migration plan is. Help desk staff should be briefed on the organization's current position and planned next steps.

*Sources: [Exchange Team Blog — July Security Updates](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/released-july-2026-exchange-server-security-updates/ba-p/4534146) · [SharePoint Blog — Copilot July 2026](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-sharepoint-blog/what-s-new-in-copilot-in-sharepoint-july-2026/ba-p/4535420) · [Teams Blog — Intelligent Call Delegation](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-teams-blog/focus-on-the-teams-phone-calls-that-matter-most-with-intelligent/ba-p/4512533)*

