## If You Take No Action

**ACR Stealer credential theft:** Employees across enterprise environments are actively being targeted by campaigns that bypass passwords and MFA by stealing the authentication tokens stored in browsers. If no awareness communication goes out and no review of conditional access policies occurs, a credential compromise is a matter of probability, not possibility. A single stolen token can grant an attacker full access to email, files, and business systems. Downstream costs include incident response, breach notification, regulatory fines, and potential cyber insurance disputes if documented controls were absent.

**Exchange 2016/2019 reaching end of support:** After October 2026, no further security patches will be issued for these systems. A mail server running known, unpatched vulnerabilities is among the most exploitable assets in any environment. Ransomware actors specifically target end-of-life mail servers because the attack methods are publicly documented and defenses cannot be updated. The business impact includes potential data loss, service disruption, regulatory breach reporting obligations, and disqualification from cyber insurance coverage. Three months is a short migration window; delay in approving budget and engaging a vendor compresses an already tight timeline.

**AI agents operating without governance:** Unmanaged agents can access data, call external systems, and execute workflows without an audit trail or access boundary. If an agent is built with overly broad permissions and accesses sensitive HR, financial, or patient data, the organization may face a regulatory exposure it is unaware of until an audit or incident surfaces it. Establishing an inventory and governance framework now costs far less than remediating an undisclosed data access event later.

